1
00:00:00,140 --> 00:00:05,450
In this video we are going to do domain analyzing of the discount microservices.

2
00:00:05,450 --> 00:00:07,760
And we will start with the domain models.

3
00:00:08,060 --> 00:00:13,130
As a domain model, we can say that we have only one domain model which is the coupon.

4
00:00:13,310 --> 00:00:15,590
And including the coupon model.

5
00:00:15,590 --> 00:00:20,150
We have several attributes ID, product name, description and amount.

6
00:00:20,150 --> 00:00:25,580
So the coupon entity represents the discount information linking to the products.

7
00:00:26,240 --> 00:00:29,300
And after that we can go to the application use cases.

8
00:00:29,510 --> 00:00:36,380
Our main use cases are Crud operations on discount coupon model including the get discount with product

9
00:00:36,380 --> 00:00:39,950
name and create update delete discount operations.

10
00:00:39,950 --> 00:00:44,420
And these use cases cover all the basic operations for managing discounts.

11
00:00:44,420 --> 00:00:49,550
And along with this, we should design our gRPC methods according to these use cases.

12
00:00:49,550 --> 00:00:55,820
And here you can see the gRPC methods and use cases that we are going to implement as a presentation

13
00:00:55,820 --> 00:00:57,710
layer and gRPC API.

14
00:00:57,710 --> 00:01:05,990
So instead of the exposing traditional Rest APIs, the discount microservices will expose gRPC endpoints.

15
00:01:05,990 --> 00:01:13,640
And in discount microservices as a presentation layer, we use Http two gRPC protocol to expose these

16
00:01:13,640 --> 00:01:14,360
endpoints.

17
00:01:14,360 --> 00:01:19,910
Here you can see the gRPC methods that we are going to expose from the discount microservices.

18
00:01:19,910 --> 00:01:27,410
These are the get, create, update and delete discount and performing the Crud use cases from our application.

19
00:01:27,410 --> 00:01:29,960
And here you can see the request URIs.

20
00:01:29,960 --> 00:01:36,470
That means every gRPC method will accept the request and respond back to the response object that we

21
00:01:36,470 --> 00:01:38,240
can define in the protobuf file.

22
00:01:38,240 --> 00:01:45,200
So gRPC services are defined using protocol buffers which are more efficient than traditional Rest API,

23
00:01:45,200 --> 00:01:48,140
particularly for inter service communications.

24
00:01:48,470 --> 00:01:54,710
So if you look at the infrastructure and underlying data structure of discount microservices, we can

25
00:01:54,710 --> 00:01:59,570
say that we have only one data store, which is the SQLite database.

26
00:01:59,570 --> 00:02:04,430
And in this database we will store coupon table in a lite databases.

27
00:02:04,430 --> 00:02:06,980
So why we use SQLite database?

28
00:02:06,980 --> 00:02:14,450
Because SQLite is a C language library that implements a small, fast and self-contained, high reliability,

29
00:02:14,450 --> 00:02:17,120
full featured SQL database engine.

30
00:02:17,450 --> 00:02:25,070
SQLite is a chosen for its simplicity and efficiency, especially for small scale data like discounts.

31
00:02:25,070 --> 00:02:30,620
It is embedded within the application and reducing the need for the additional infrastructure.

32
00:02:30,620 --> 00:02:37,190
And there are lots of advantages of SQLite we can use embedded within the application, providing high

33
00:02:37,190 --> 00:02:43,610
performance and suitable for lightweight and straightforward operations, and it simplifies deployment

34
00:02:43,610 --> 00:02:46,520
without needing a separate database server.

35
00:02:46,730 --> 00:02:51,590
So this setup aligned with the need for the high performance in the discount microservices.

